    "last_edit_date" : 1409909264,
    "creation_date" : 1409905113,
    "answer_id" : 25681447,
    "question_id" : 2059431,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>In Eclipse</strong></p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Right click on the <code>pom.xml</code></li>\n<li>Select <code>Run As</code> -> <code>Maven generate-sources</code><br>\nit will generate the source by default in .m2 folder</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><strong>Pre-Requisite:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Maven should be configured with Eclipse.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 322981,
      "reputation" : 346727,
      "user_id" : 642706,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 58,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/ZWEI3.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Basil Bourque",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/642706/basil-bourque"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1442960739,
    "creation_date" : 1442960739,
    "answer_id" : 32727993,
    "question_id" : 2059431,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<h1>NetBeans, Context-Click</h1>\n\n<p>In <a href=\"https://netbeans.org/features/index.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">NetBeans 8</a> with a Maven-driven project, merely context-click on the jar file list item of the dependency in which you are interested. Choose <code>Download Sources</code>. Wait a moment and NetBeans will automatically download and install the source code, if available. </p>\n\n<p>Similarly you can choose <code>Download Javadoc</code> to get the doc locally installed. Then you can context-click some code in the editor and choose to see the JavaDoc. </p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/O12sq.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/O12sq.png\" alt=\"screen shot of context-menu item &quot;Download Sources&quot; being chosen in a NetBeans 8 project driven by Maven\"></a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 267283,
      "reputation" : 1067,
      "user_id" : 555366,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b590bd16b90bffa5a25f4fbbd17ede80?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Maddin",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/555366/maddin"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 22,
    "last_activity_date" : 1514727484,
    "last_edit_date" : 1514727484,
    "creation_date" : 1460036966,
    "answer_id" : 36478213,
    "question_id" : 2059431,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>To download any artifact use </p>\n\n<pre><code>mvn dependency:get -Dartifact=groupId:artifactId:version:packaging:classifier\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>For Groovy sources this would be </p>\n\n<pre><code>mvn dependency:get -Dartifact=org.codehaus.groovy:groovy-all:2.4.6:jar:sources\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>For Groovy's javadoc you would use</p>\n\n<pre><code>mvn dependency:get -Dartifact=org.codehaus.groovy:groovy-all:2.4.6:jar:javadoc\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This puts the given artifact into your local Maven repository, i.e. usually <code>$HOME/.m2/repository</code>.</p>\n\n<p><code>dependency:sources</code> just downloads the project dependencies' sources, not the plugins sources nor the sources of dependencies defined inside plugins.</p>\n"
  }, {
